  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 23.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Ornan's offer to David of the threshing-floor and all its belongings, as a gift, reminds of Ephron's offer to Abraham (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 23:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Ornan's prompt offer of gift was, perhaps, all the prompter from the desire to render every assistance to the staying of the plague. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For burnt offerings ...  for the meat offering.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The whole code of regulations for offerings - sin offering, trespass offering, peace offering, burnt offering, meat and drink offering - is to be found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 1-7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As regards the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "burnt offering",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 6:8-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It was called ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "עֹלָה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from its \"ascending\" accepted to heaven, or else from its being put up or raised up (Hiph. conjugation) on the altar; and sometimes ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "כָּלִיל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", from being \"wholly\" consumed. The sin and trespass offerings were for special sins, but this was of a more comprehensive kind and of much greater dignity, as standing for the \"purging of the conscience.\" The entire consuming of the sacrifice signified the unqualified self-surrender of him who brought the sacrifice. It was a voluntary offering, the offerer laid his hand on the head of the victim, and the blood of the victim was sprinkled round about the altar. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The meat offering",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מִנְחָה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") is fully described in Leviticus it.; Leviticus 6:14-23. It was an offering without blood, and therefore was an accompaniment of an offering of blood. It was composed of flour or cakes, prepared with salt, oil, and frank-incense - the salt emblematic of non-decay; the oil, of spiritual grace; and the frankincense, of acceptable fragrance. A portion of this offering was to be burnt, and a portion eaten by the priests in the court, unless it was for a priest himself, when all must be burnt. Meantime a drink offering of wine was, in fact, a part of the meat offering itself (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 29:40, 41",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 23:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 15:4-7, 9, 10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The material of the meat offering might be the green or fresh-gathered ears of corn. The Septuagint translates ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δῶρον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Luther, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "speis-opfer",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and it need scarcely be said that our Authorized Version ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "meat",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " offering exhibits only the generic employment of the word \"meat\" for food. 1 Chronicles 21:23",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
